headline: MSNBC hosts clash over which Democratic presidential candidate could beat Trump
subHeadline: Guests: Donny Deutsch and Lawrence O'Donnell spar during Democratic debate analysis; reaction on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.sentences: Hi, I'm Greg Gutfeld with Dagen McDowell, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and she rode to work on a cricket, Dana Perino. “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: (FOREIGN LANGUAGE).

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, HOST
utterances.sentences: That's terrible.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, I am bilingual, but do you see me showing off?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: (SPOKEN IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE).

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: (SPOKEN IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE).

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: (SPOKEN IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE).

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Now, it's not English but it's easy to figure out. It's called pandering, and it was muy loco. Now try to follow this and it's in English.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I don't believe only in reproductive freedom. I believe in reproductive justice.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: And what that means is just because a woman or -- let's also not forget someone in the trans community -- a trans female --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: -- is poor, doesn't mean they shouldn't have the right to exercise that right to choose. And so, I absolutely would cover the right to have an abortion.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: (FOREIGN LANGUAGE), which is Yiddish for you lost me. But the debate wasn't about facts. It was about who could out-left each other which left most Americans out of the conversation.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Who here would abolish their private health insurance in favor of a government-run plan? Just a show of hands to start out with.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Yes, we're supposed to be for 74 percent tax rate on the wealthy. Yes, we're supposed to be for free college.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: We must begin impeachment now.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I think we have a serious problem in our country with corporate consolidation. One of the most aggressive bills in the Senate to deal with corporate consolidation is mine about corporate consolidation of the act sector. To check the corporate consolidation and let the free market work.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: There's way too much consolidation now in giant industries in this country.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: The immigrants didn't do that to you. The big corporations did that to you.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: The one percent did that to you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Sounded like a campus sit-in, although it's missing the body odor. The problem wasn't just the candidates thought, but the moderators who are no different than the candidates, eliminating any moderation. It was MSNBC interviewing future hosts of MSNBC.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Democrats have been talking about the pay gap for decades. What would you do to ensure that women are paid fairly in this country?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Would you support a 70 percent individual marginal tax rate? Yes, no, we're passed.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: How would you address income inequality?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Parts of Miami Beach and the Keys could be underwater in our lifetime. Does your plan save Miami?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Not too challenging. Instead, they were like parents quizzing their own brats at the school spelling bee. OK, Billy, the next word is Billy. Can you spell your own name, Billy? Very good, Billy. They just ask the candidates about their ends, never the means, giving them a free ride on all the free stuff. So they've all echoed every left-wing wish in unison, no abortion restriction, no border enforcements, skyrocketing taxes, punishing evil corporations, blah, blah, blah, but sometimes in Spanish.  The result, as Trump said, boring, (SPOKEN IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE), because the left-wing litmus test creates clones. Nothing new, nothing refreshing, nothing human, and nothing fun, let alone interesting. There's no wit, irony, or real moments, just posturing. Nothing authentic, which is what you need to beat Trump. So this event was as serious as a funeral maybe because it was. At least the moderates in that party, for now, are dead.  All right, so we'll just go around the horn here. Your thoughts on the debate winners, losers?

utterances.speaker: DAGEN MCDOWELL, HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, I think Elizabeth Warren, ultimately, is a huge, huge loser. Doing her best --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, really.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: -- Tracy flick. Oh, oh, putting her hand in the air for taking health insurance or private insurance away from a 180 million people. Look around the stage. Who else has their hand in the air? Bill de Blasio, when you're in company with that idiot Lerch -- is that what you call --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I might have called him a Lerch.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: Yes, maybe not -- you're in trouble. She's going to be held to that. She's co-sponsored Bernie Sanders' Medicare for all bill, not only gets rid of private insurance, also gets rid of Medicare as we know it. And again, how do you win anybody over the age of 50 with them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Juan, what were your thoughts? This is your team. Who surprised you, who didn't?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, I said I thought Castro would do well, and I think he was the breakout star of the night.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, I mean, he did a lot of hard work on Beto.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, I think he really, you know, exposed Beto in terms of lack of knowledge on a key issue for Democrats which is immigration.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And he took a strong stand and said he's teed off about it, you know. So, I think that really is something that people gonna remember from last night. I think Warren was a total winner though, if you ask me who stood apart. She's definitely dominated the early part of the debates. Some people think -- you would think the moderators went to her too often, although they say she didn't interrupt and jump-in in the second half.  But I think, clearly, given that she went as the leader in the polls, the only person in double digit polling. I think she came out of it better than she went in. I think -- one thing I was thinking about as I was listening to you, Greg, was the audience that count here are Democratic primary voters, not Republicans.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Of course.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And so, it seems to me it's not the audience that says that Trump shot somebody on Fifth Avenue, I don't care. These are people who have strong feelings about policies and ideas. And I think that the reason O'Rourke, Booker, Castro spoke in Spanish, by the way, is because, guess what? One, it was in Miami, but two, Telemundo, Univision, all these places will play clips from the debate. And if you have it in Spanish they can control that message and be very clear about what they want to convey to a growing sector of the Democratic voting.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: They should have spoked in Russian, since they're controlling the election, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.sentences: That's true. I actually have to agree with Juan. I think Castro was the biggest breakout star. He was polished, he was prepared. He looked presidential. I can see him on the ticket. De Blasio actually surprised me. He looked like he had a little fight there, and maybe because he's 6'9'', and he definitely filled up a lot of room on the stage --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But if you put Julio and de Blasio put together.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's a little awkward. Booker got the most talk-time. I think MSNBC wanted to give him a boost. He's just a little too earnest. And I'm tired of hearing about Newark. And I can't stop looking at his bottom teeth and his bulging eyeballs. Other than that, he did fine. Beto, where's this great Beto personality everyone's talking about? Beto did not show up. He had dead eyes. He looked tired. He looked pale. He needs some sun. I think he said the greatest geopolitical threat was global warming? Complete joke.  Warren, I guess if I didn't know that she was leading in the polls with this group, I wouldn't even know that she won the debate. She didn't have any memorable lines. I wasn't that impressed by her. And what you said is death. If you wanted to take away 180 million people in private healthcare --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: In the general election, complete toast. The most exciting part was the technical glitch. That's how boring it was. The audience was yawning the whole time. The audience wasn't rocking. No one showed their personality. No one was that competitive. I mean, some people picked a fight but didn't finish it. No one really showed any sort of knockout power or killer instinct out there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But you know -- I know you're a ratings guy. So I was curious, you know, were people watching? Because Greg said -- Greg and Trump said boring, right? Well, it wasn't about Trump. So for Mr. Narcissist, of course, it was boring. But guess what? Like 15-plus-million people watch this debate.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The last Republican primary on Fox News it was 24 million.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no. Comparing it to what the Democrats did last time, this is about the same. And it seems to me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Apples and oranges.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Biggest winner?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Mitch McConnell.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I'll tell you why. So Trump's name is mentioned, but not a lot.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Nope.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Biden's name never came up.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All of them are asked the question, how are you going to deal with Mitch McConnell? And none of them said, well, when I'm at the top of the ticket I'm going to make sure that the Democrats win back the Senate. And that's how we're going to deal with Mitch McConnell. We're going to beat him in his race in Kentucky.  And instead, they're basically were like, well, we have to work on the filibuster and couple of other things and --. Basically, I think that they were just seeding the ground to the Republicans on the Senate side, and I think Mitch McConnell was the biggest winner.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Follow-up question, if I may. Who do you think was the most authentic person?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: You know, I have to say that Jay Inslee, the governor of Washington, to me had a better debate that people would have thought.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I agree.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Thank you. He is authentic. Wasn't he, essentially, a climate change -- we're going to do this --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: But he's a governor. It's hard to win state-wide. You know, emission in Washington State, though, have not gone down. And I think that he's going to have to -- some proof points to work on.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know, I'm surprised because I think that you're right. And I also think Amy Klobuchar, if you're thinking about a moderate if Biden slips, someone who can occupy --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah. But Castro, definitely, took Beto out of that lane. That particular lane. It's like you're done.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know who else took Beto out of the lane? Being on the cover of Vanity Fair when nobody knew you. That just got everybody so mad. Like all of his peers are like who the hell is this guy?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think Julian probably just said I'd take care of this.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: You know who's mad now? Anybody who gave Beto money. He had that look on his face like he was worried about that --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: You know my prediction yesterday was that he would raise $1 million after this debate. And again, this debate was not for Republicans or conservatives, it was for that -- he could actually still have some support out there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: All right, the candidates also revealed their immigration plans. Here's a hint, open borders.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It was a night of some far-left ideas, and that didn't stop when it came to the topic of immigration with some of the candidates seeming to basically endorse open borders.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I would follow that up in my first 100 days with immigration reform that will honor asylum claims that would put undocumented immigrants as long as they haven't committed a serious crime on a pathway to citizenship. My plan also includes getting rid of section 1325 of the immigration and nationality act. Criminalize is coming across the border.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: We would not detain any families fleeing violence, and then we'd re-write our immigration laws in our own image. Free dreamers forever from any fear of deportation by making them U.S. citizens here in this country.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: The separation of children from families doesn't just go on in our borders, it happens in our community as ICE is ripping away parents from their American children, spouses and the like, and creating fear in cities all across this country, where parents are afraid to even drop their kids off to school or go to work --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: But at least one Democrat seems to be retreating. Here's Julian Castro.

utterances.speaker: JULIAN CASTRO, FORMER SECRETARY OF HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT
utterances.sentences: I'm for decriminalizing, not legalizing. There's still civil penalties, people are still part of a court process, people are still subject to the laws of the United States. They still go through a process. Also, open borders is a right-wing talking point. We have 654 miles of fencing, we have thousands of border personnel, we have planes, we have helicopters, we have boats, we have guns, we have security cameras, nobody has called for open borders.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse, what do you think of that?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I mean, they have. Beto saying he doesn't want a wall. I mean, Trump wants to issue deportation and they want to issue invitation. That's what their policy adds up to. That's what they're all about. They wanted to pull back border patrol from the front line. They don't want to fund the border patrol. They want to put a cap on the beds in the detention facilities. And they're not doing anything to stop the influx. All their doing is when they get here they want to catch and release. So, that's open borders. Enough said. I think what the problem is with the Democrats is that they've now gone so far on immigration. They've gone so far on taxes and spending, and then ripping private healthcare away in reparations. It's the most radical progressive crop of candidates you've ever seen. And what happened with President Obama when he went so far-left, so much change in such a short period of time, he got shellacked so hard at the end of his term, the Democrats were out of power so far since they hadn't been in 1920. The American people can't handle all of that radical change that quickly. And this crop of Democrats is doing it twice as fast and twice as crazy, and it's really going to hurt them.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But wait a second, Jesse. I mean, just this very day you see Nancy Pelosi saying, oh, yeah, OK, I'll go along because the children come first. And we want to make sure that there's not abuse of these children in this horrible situation down at the border. So, don't Democrats get credit?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: What took her 4 months?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: What took her 4 months? What about the guy who said we have an invasion that we need to send the military, we need build the wall? Do you think there's a reason the Democrats might say, you know what? You're not sincere about helping anybody. You're playing politics with immigration.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK. So there is a crisis now?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: There's a humanitarian issue with --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's why it's not a terrorist attack. That's like workplace violence all over again.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No. What I'm saying to you -- so yesterday when you listened to Julian Castro, and I think he's right. This is a Republican talking point. We have -- nobody is calling for open borders. But you do have a problem in terms of the zero tolerance policy about metering asylum claims. Now, even the officers who represents the folks who do asylum are suing the government joining with the ACLU to say to remain in Mexico policy is not good. Not in keeping with U.S. values. Not making them and their jobs easier or more efficient. So, to me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Can you close the asylum loop hole, Juan? And you treat the Central-American migrants the same way you treat the Mexicans.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That's the law.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That will keep them in Mexico so you don't have --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Let me get Greg in, because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- obey the law. The law right now as stance --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I agree. I obeyed the law and enforced the law.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Greg, Beto O'Rourke in the debate, he said we would not detain anyone that is fleeing violence. Well, that's all of them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah. The thing is they have -- they have no process. They have no system. They have wishes, but they can't explain what to do. You know, who -- we know who caused the children's crisis. It was activists who egged on the caravans. Remember where this started. It was this C-word, the caravans, which caused us to react. If the Democrats -- if the Congress had listened to Trump, a child would be alive that died, because he was talking about preventing this from happening. When you have thousands and thousands of people coming, when you have a large movement of people coming, there are risks, people will get hurt, people will die, it happens, and it's terrible. It wouldn't have happened if you had actually addressed the problem when all of us were talking about the problem. But the point is these politicians are too scared to address this problem because of the activists consensus media. You know they -- Trump will nail this in a debate if he says who do you want to decide our immigration policy, other countries or us? That's the simplest question. And the Dems -- Democrats can't decide on that question the same way they can't decide on homelessness, or they can't decide on law and order. Think about it. It's not the victim. It's always the criminal. It's not the store owner. It's always the guy loitering in front of the store. It's not the citizen who decide immigration, it's the other country. In each one of this situation, the Democrats never pick the right side and never have a process.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Let me just quickly respond and say I think we picked the right side because American values are -- we're a country of immigrants. We welcome people --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What's the process?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And after World War II when we realized that we have kept out Jewish people fleeing the Germans, we've said, you know what? We're going to change --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Dagen, while we've been on air and during this block, the House has passed the Senate bill. This is for the emergency money that the administration has asked for, for the last few months. And I think that, politically, I just -- what you think about the Democrats, they want to go on their recess and they didn't have to go to recess and not have all this dealt with because the tide was turning on the narrative. I hate that word. But the storyline was going to follow them that they were blocking resources to help take care of these kids.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: Better late than never, should have happened months ago. And I want the Democrats to step up and talk about why all of these people are trying to pour into the United States is because the economy is so strong, quite frankly. That you have in terms of job openings in this country, you have a record number. A difference between job openings and unemployed in this nation, it's about 1.62-million more jobs available here. And the strange thing about all these Democratic policies is it's going to drive the economy into a recession if one of them got elected, and that mean we would actually slow immigration into the United States.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And the corrupt Central-American countries don't spend any money on welfare, on housing, on healthcare. They push all of their poor people north --

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: There's no rule of law.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- and that's their game plan.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: And decriminalizing, basically, is the same thing as legalizing. It's an open borders.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Dagen, I don't think Mexicans are coming across the borders in increasing numbers. Is these Central-Americans, and the reason they're fleeing is because of the terrible economy, but also violence and oppression. That's the reason.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right, the real fireworks happened after the debate when an MSNBC panel claimed no Democratic candidate could beat Donald Trump. You've got to see, it's a must-see meltdown from the liberal host, next on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: The Democratic candidates may have tried to sound tough last night, but not everyone on the left agrees. And MSNBC host causing chaos at the network after he said none of those candidates can beat Donald Trump. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: My issue, unfortunately, and do not shoot the messenger, is the messenger. I do not believe Elizabeth Warren on stage with Donald Trump beats him.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Who could beat Trump? And did you see anyone on stage tonight that could beat Trump?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I'm still sticking with an idealized version of -- no - - the Joe Biden we want. I still in my heart of hearts don't see anyone on that stage tonight that would beat Trump.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Let's just identify this for what it is.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: And then --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Pure guess work a year and a half away --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Absolutely.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: And so, it has -- tonight, I say this respectfully, zero value.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Don't tell me it has zero value.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: It's a guess. It's a wild guess.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: It's understanding human behavior.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: It's a wild guess. There's no science in it.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: Greg, just have at it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I say, respectfully, you suck.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But you know what? That's nothing compares to stuff that happens here on THE FIVE. I don't see that as like fireworks.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Can I say amen.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know what? Both of them are correct. And I can't believe I'm saying Donnie Deutsch is correct. But they have a problem with Trump. He's redefine how you perceive politicians. You can't just act like a politician, you know, pregnant pauses, stately, you know, dressed a certain way and people will just leave you alone. You have to be authentic. And that's a problem because you can't out-authenticate someone who pretty much broke the mold. You can say Trump is -- all these bad things, but you can say he's as about authentic as you're going to get. This Queen real estate tycoon is what you get, so none of those people so far have that. But Bernie is quite of authentic and that's what -- I think Bernie still has -- is a force -- and I think Liz Warren could come up. But also, LOD is correct too, and that it's still really early. And you can't write anybody off yet.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: LOD?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Lawrence O'Donnell.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I know, but seriously?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It takes time.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK. Like the new AOC.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: But you know what? This was evidence, though, that if you are on MSNBC, if you're on that network, you must be belching bile about Trump sneering, sobbing, or hyperventilating, but you can't talk about reality. And that's why Hillary lost.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah. I mean, LOD might have just wanted to shut Donnie down because he didn't want to hear that on a night when the Democrats were supposed to shine. And they didn't shine. There were no stars on that stage. The only star was Rachael Maddow. I don't include Chuck Todd in that. Rachel Maddow was a legit star. And none of those people rose to the occasion last night. None of them were competitive enough, none of them filled up the screen enough. If you can put Donald Trump on the stage next to any of these people in a one-on-one, he'd eat their lunch, clean their clock. It wouldn't even be competitive. And I'm not so sure there's anybody tonight that's going to be like that either. Donny is thinking with his heart, Lawrence is thinking with his head. It's not science. They say it's political science, but politics is about emotion, it's about a connection you have - a visceral connection with a candidate and whether you can make that connection with the people, and that's unbreakable. And right now no one's even close to doing that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You be not even Eric Swalwell?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Not even little there.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.sentences: His claim to fame is an ad about a poopy diaper. So Donny Deutsch said last night, this is about who is the bully that can beat the bully. The guy who would fill up the screen next to Trump was Bill de Blasio and he certainly was a bully. He shouted down Savannah Guthrie when she was trying to go to break last night. So--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It is pretty amazing that this very unlikable person, unpopular person has this basically Don Quixote quest to become the President of the United States. And I'm sure, a bunch of them are looking around going, "Who are you to be here and to tell us that?" As to the argument is there anybody on that stage, remember incumbent Presidents usually get reelected, especially if there's a good economy. And even if people were like, "Well, he's not really kind of guy", but they're not going to sacrifice their financial security for four years for somebody who can't articulate an economic message. There's not.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I think that - well, first of all let me just say. utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: (SPOKEN IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE).

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Now, it's not English but it's easy to figure out. It's called pandering, and it was muy loco. Now try to follow this and it's in English.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I don't believe only in reproductive freedom. I believe in reproductive justice.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: And what that means is just because a woman or -- let's also not forget someone in the trans community -- a trans female --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: -- is poor, doesn't mean they shouldn't have the right to exercise that right to choose. And so, I absolutely would cover the right to have an abortion.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: (FOREIGN LANGUAGE), which is Yiddish for you lost me. But the debate wasn't about facts. It was about who could out-left each other which left most Americans out of the conversation.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Who here would abolish their private health insurance in favor of a government-run plan? Just a show of hands to start out with.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Yes, we're supposed to be for 74 percent tax rate on the wealthy. Yes, we're supposed to be for free college.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: We must begin impeachment now.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I think we have a serious problem in our country with corporate consolidation. One of the most aggressive bills in the Senate to deal with corporate consolidation is mine about corporate consolidation of the act sector. To check the corporate consolidation and let the free market work.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: There's way too much consolidation now in giant industries in this country.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: The immigrants didn't do that to you. The big corporations did that to you.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: The one percent did that to you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Sounded like a campus sit-in, although it's missing the body odor. The problem wasn't just the candidates thought, but the moderators who are no different than the candidates, eliminating any moderation. It was MSNBC interviewing future hosts of MSNBC.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Democrats have been talking about the pay gap for decades. What would you do to ensure that women are paid fairly in this country?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Would you support a 70 percent individual marginal tax rate? Yes, no, we're passed.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: How would you address income inequality?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Parts of Miami Beach and the Keys could be underwater in our lifetime. Does your plan save Miami?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Not too challenging. Instead, they were like parents quizzing their own brats at the school spelling bee. OK, Billy, the next word is Billy. Can you spell your own name, Billy? Very good, Billy. They just ask the candidates about their ends, never the means, giving them a free ride on all the free stuff. So they've all echoed every left-wing wish in unison, no abortion restriction, no border enforcements, skyrocketing taxes, punishing evil corporations, blah, blah, blah, but sometimes in Spanish. The result, as Trump said, boring, (SPOKEN IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE), because the left-wing litmus test creates clones. Nothing new, nothing refreshing, nothing human, and nothing fun, let alone interesting. There's no wit, irony, or real moments, just posturing. Nothing authentic, which is what you need to beat Trump. So this event was as serious as a funeral maybe because it was. At least the moderates in that party, for now, are dead. All right, so we'll just go around the horn here. Your thoughts on the debate winners, losers?

utterances.speaker: DAGEN MCDOWELL, HOST
utterances.utterance: Well, I think Elizabeth Warren, ultimately, is a huge, huge loser. Doing her best --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, really.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: -- Tracy flick. Oh, oh, putting her hand in the air for taking health insurance or private insurance away from a 180 million people. Look around the stage. Who else has their hand in the air? Bill de Blasio, when you're in company with that idiot Lerch -- is that what you call --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I might have called him a Lerch.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Yes, maybe not -- you're in trouble. She's going to be held to that. She's co-sponsored Bernie Sanders' Medicare for all bill, not only gets rid of private insurance, also gets rid of Medicare as we know it. And again, how do you win anybody over the age of 50 with them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Juan, what were your thoughts? This is your team. Who surprised you, who didn't?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, HOST
utterances.utterance: Well, I said I thought Castro would do well, and I think he was the breakout star of the night.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, I mean, he did a lot of hard work on Beto.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, I think he really, you know, exposed Beto in terms of lack of knowledge on a key issue for Democrats which is immigration.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And he took a strong stand and said he's teed off about it, you know. So, I think that really is something that people gonna remember from last night. I think Warren was a total winner though, if you ask me who stood apart. She's definitely dominated the early part of the debates. Some people think -- you would think the moderators went to her too often, although they say she didn't interrupt and jump-in in the second half. But I think, clearly, given that she went as the leader in the polls, the only person in double digit polling. I think she came out of it better than she went in. I think -- one thing I was thinking about as I was listening to you, Greg, was the audience that count here are Democratic primary voters, not Republicans.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Of course.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And so, it seems to me it's not the audience that says that Trump shot somebody on Fifth Avenue, I don't care. These are people who have strong feelings about policies and ideas. And I think that the reason O'Rourke, Booker, Castro spoke in Spanish, by the way, is because, guess what? One, it was in Miami, but two, Telemundo, Univision, all these places will play clips from the debate. And if you have it in Spanish they can control that message and be very clear about what they want to convey to a growing sector of the Democratic voting.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: They should have spoked in Russian, since they're controlling the election, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.utterance: That's true. I actually have to agree with Juan. I think Castro was the biggest breakout star. He was polished, he was prepared. He looked presidential. I can see him on the ticket. De Blasio actually surprised me. He looked like he had a little fight there, and maybe because he's 6'9'', and he definitely filled up a lot of room on the stage --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But if you put Julio and de Blasio put together.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's a little awkward. Booker got the most talk-time. I think MSNBC wanted to give him a boost. He's just a little too earnest. And I'm tired of hearing about Newark. And I can't stop looking at his bottom teeth and his bulging eyeballs. Other than that, he did fine. Beto, where's this great Beto personality everyone's talking about? Beto did not show up. He had dead eyes. He looked tired. He looked pale. He needs some sun. I think he said the greatest geopolitical threat was global warming? Complete joke. Warren, I guess if I didn't know that she was leading in the polls with this group, I wouldn't even know that she won the debate. She didn't have any memorable lines. I wasn't that impressed by her. And what you said is death. If you wanted to take away 180 million people in private healthcare --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: In the general election, complete toast. The most exciting part was the technical glitch. That's how boring it was. The audience was yawning the whole time. The audience wasn't rocking. No one showed their personality. No one was that competitive. I mean, some people picked a fight but didn't finish it. No one really showed any sort of knockout power or killer instinct out there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But you know -- I know you're a ratings guy. So I was curious, you know, were people watching? Because Greg said -- Greg and Trump said boring, right? Well, it wasn't about Trump. So for Mr. Narcissist, of course, it was boring. But guess what? Like 15-plus-million people watch this debate.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The last Republican primary on Fox News it was 24 million.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no. Comparing it to what the Democrats did last time, this is about the same. And it seems to me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Apples and oranges.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Biggest winner?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Mitch McConnell.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'll tell you why. So Trump's name is mentioned, but not a lot.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Nope.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Biden's name never came up.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All of them are asked the question, how are you going to deal with Mitch McConnell? And none of them said, well, when I'm at the top of the ticket I'm going to make sure that the Democrats win back the Senate. And that's how we're going to deal with Mitch McConnell. We're going to beat him in his race in Kentucky. And instead, they're basically were like, well, we have to work on the filibuster and couple of other things and --. Basically, I think that they were just seeding the ground to the Republicans on the Senate side, and I think Mitch McConnell was the biggest winner.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Follow-up question, if I may. Who do you think was the most authentic person?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You know, I have to say that Jay Inslee, the governor of Washington, to me had a better debate that people would have thought.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I agree.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Thank you. He is authentic. Wasn't he, essentially, a climate change -- we're going to do this --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But he's a governor. It's hard to win state-wide. You know, emission in Washington State, though, have not gone down. And I think that he's going to have to -- some proof points to work on.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know, I'm surprised because I think that you're right. And I also think Amy Klobuchar, if you're thinking about a moderate if Biden slips, someone who can occupy --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah. But Castro, definitely, took Beto out of that lane. That particular lane. It's like you're done.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know who else took Beto out of the lane? Being on the cover of Vanity Fair when nobody knew you. That just got everybody so mad. Like all of his peers are like who the hell is this guy?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think Julian probably just said I'd take care of this.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: You know who's mad now? Anybody who gave Beto money. He had that look on his face like he was worried about that --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You know my prediction yesterday was that he would raise $1 million after this debate. And again, this debate was not for Republicans or conservatives, it was for that -- he could actually still have some support out there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right, the candidates also revealed their immigration plans. Here's a hint, open borders.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It was a night of some far-left ideas, and that didn't stop when it came to the topic of immigration with some of the candidates seeming to basically endorse open borders.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I would follow that up in my first 100 days with immigration reform that will honor asylum claims that would put undocumented immigrants as long as they haven't committed a serious crime on a pathway to citizenship. My plan also includes getting rid of section 1325 of the immigration and nationality act. Criminalize is coming across the border.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: We would not detain any families fleeing violence, and then we'd re-write our immigration laws in our own image. Free dreamers forever from any fear of deportation by making them U.S. citizens here in this country.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: The separation of children from families doesn't just go on in our borders, it happens in our community as ICE is ripping away parents from their American children, spouses and the like, and creating fear in cities all across this country, where parents are afraid to even drop their kids off to school or go to work --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But at least one Democrat seems to be retreating. Here's Julian Castro.

utterances.speaker: JULIAN CASTRO, FORMER SECRETARY OF HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT
utterances.utterance: I'm for decriminalizing, not legalizing. There's still civil penalties, people are still part of a court process, people are still subject to the laws of the United States. They still go through a process. Also, open borders is a right-wing talking point. We have 654 miles of fencing, we have thousands of border personnel, we have planes, we have helicopters, we have boats, we have guns, we have security cameras, nobody has called for open borders.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse, what do you think of that?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean, they have. Beto saying he doesn't want a wall. I mean, Trump wants to issue deportation and they want to issue invitation. That's what their policy adds up to. That's what they're all about. They wanted to pull back border patrol from the front line. They don't want to fund the border patrol. They want to put a cap on the beds in the detention facilities. And they're not doing anything to stop the influx. All their doing is when they get here they want to catch and release. So, that's open borders. Enough said. I think what the problem is with the Democrats is that they've now gone so far on immigration. They've gone so far on taxes and spending, and then ripping private healthcare away in reparations. It's the most radical progressive crop of candidates you've ever seen. And what happened with President Obama when he went so far-left, so much change in such a short period of time, he got shellacked so hard at the end of his term, the Democrats were out of power so far since they hadn't been in 1920. The American people can't handle all of that radical change that quickly. And this crop of Democrats is doing it twice as fast and twice as crazy, and it's really going to hurt them.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But wait a second, Jesse. I mean, just this very day you see Nancy Pelosi saying, oh, yeah, OK, I'll go along because the children come first. And we want to make sure that there's not abuse of these children in this horrible situation down at the border. So, don't Democrats get credit?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What took her 4 months?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What took her 4 months? What about the guy who said we have an invasion that we need to send the military, we need build the wall? Do you think there's a reason the Democrats might say, you know what? You're not sincere about helping anybody. You're playing politics with immigration.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK. So there is a crisis now?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: There's a humanitarian issue with --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's why it's not a terrorist attack. That's like workplace violence all over again.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No. What I'm saying to you -- so yesterday when you listened to Julian Castro, and I think he's right. This is a Republican talking point. We have -- nobody is calling for open borders. But you do have a problem in terms of the zero tolerance policy about metering asylum claims. Now, even the officers who represents the folks who do asylum are suing the government joining with the ACLU to say to remain in Mexico policy is not good. Not in keeping with U.S. values. Not making them and their jobs easier or more efficient. So, to me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Can you close the asylum loop hole, Juan? And you treat the Central-American migrants the same way you treat the Mexicans.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's the law.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That will keep them in Mexico so you don't have --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Let me get Greg in, because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- obey the law. The law right now as stance --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I agree. I obeyed the law and enforced the law.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Greg, Beto O'Rourke in the debate, he said we would not detain anyone that is fleeing violence. Well, that's all of them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. The thing is they have -- they have no process. They have no system. They have wishes, but they can't explain what to do. You know, who -- we know who caused the children's crisis. It was activists who egged on the caravans. Remember where this started. It was this C-word, the caravans, which caused us to react. If the Democrats -- if the Congress had listened to Trump, a child would be alive that died, because he was talking about preventing this from happening. When you have thousands and thousands of people coming, when you have a large movement of people coming, there are risks, people will get hurt, people will die, it happens, and it's terrible. It wouldn't have happened if you had actually addressed the problem when all of us were talking about the problem. But the point is these politicians are too scared to address this problem because of the activists consensus media. You know they -- Trump will nail this in a debate if he says who do you want to decide our immigration policy, other countries or us? That's the simplest question. And the Dems -- Democrats can't decide on that question the same way they can't decide on homelessness, or they can't decide on law and order. Think about it. It's not the victim. It's always the criminal. It's not the store owner. It's always the guy loitering in front of the store. It's not the citizen who decide immigration, it's the other country. In each one of this situation, the Democrats never pick the right side and never have a process.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let me just quickly respond and say I think we picked the right side because American values are -- we're a country of immigrants. We welcome people --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What's the process?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And after World War II when we realized that we have kept out Jewish people fleeing the Germans, we've said, you know what? We're going to change --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Dagen, while we've been on air and during this block, the House has passed the Senate bill. This is for the emergency money that the administration has asked for, for the last few months. And I think that, politically, I just -- what you think about the Democrats, they want to go on their recess and they didn't have to go to recess and not have all this dealt with because the tide was turning on the narrative. I hate that word. But the storyline was going to follow them that they were blocking resources to help take care of these kids.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Better late than never, should have happened months ago. And I want the Democrats to step up and talk about why all of these people are trying to pour into the United States is because the economy is so strong, quite frankly. That you have in terms of job openings in this country, you have a record number. A difference between job openings and unemployed in this nation, it's about 1.62-million more jobs available here. And the strange thing about all these Democratic policies is it's going to drive the economy into a recession if one of them got elected, and that mean we would actually slow immigration into the United States.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And the corrupt Central-American countries don't spend any money on welfare, on housing, on healthcare. They push all of their poor people north --

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: There's no rule of law.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- and that's their game plan.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: And decriminalizing, basically, is the same thing as legalizing. It's an open borders.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dagen, I don't think Mexicans are coming across the borders in increasing numbers. Is these Central-Americans, and the reason they're fleeing is because of the terrible economy, but also violence and oppression. That's the reason.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right, the real fireworks happened after the debate when an MSNBC panel claimed no Democratic candidate could beat Donald Trump. You've got to see, it's a must-see meltdown from the liberal host, next on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: The Democratic candidates may have tried to sound tough last night, but not everyone on the left agrees. And MSNBC host causing chaos at the network after he said none of those candidates can beat Donald Trump. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: My issue, unfortunately, and do not shoot the messenger, is the messenger. I do not believe Elizabeth Warren on stage with Donald Trump beats him.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Who could beat Trump? And did you see anyone on stage tonight that could beat Trump?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I'm still sticking with an idealized version of -- no - - the Joe Biden we want. I still in my heart of hearts don't see anyone on that stage tonight that would beat Trump.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Let's just identify this for what it is.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: And then --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Pure guess work a year and a half away --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Absolutely.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: And so, it has -- tonight, I say this respectfully, zero value.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Don't tell me it has zero value.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It's a guess. It's a wild guess.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It's understanding human behavior.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It's a wild guess. There's no science in it.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Greg, just have at it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I say, respectfully, you suck.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But you know what? That's nothing compares to stuff that happens here on THE FIVE. I don't see that as like fireworks.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Can I say amen.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what? Both of them are correct. And I can't believe I'm saying Donnie Deutsch is correct. But they have a problem with Trump. He's redefine how you perceive politicians. You can't just act like a politician, you know, pregnant pauses, stately, you know, dressed a certain way and people will just leave you alone. You have to be authentic. And that's a problem because you can't out-authenticate someone who pretty much broke the mold. You can say Trump is -- all these bad things, but you can say he's as about authentic as you're going to get. This Queen real estate tycoon is what you get, so none of those people so far have that. But Bernie is quite of authentic and that's what -- I think Bernie still has -- is a force -- and I think Liz Warren could come up. But also, LOD is correct too, and that it's still really early. And you can't write anybody off yet.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: LOD?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Lawrence O'Donnell.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I know, but seriously?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It takes time.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK. Like the new AOC.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: But you know what? This was evidence, though, that if you are on MSNBC, if you're on that network, you must be belching bile about Trump sneering, sobbing, or hyperventilating, but you can't talk about reality. And that's why Hillary lost.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I mean, LOD might have just wanted to shut Donnie down because he didn't want to hear that on a night when the Democrats were supposed to shine. And they didn't shine. There were no stars on that stage. The only star was Rachael Maddow. I don't include Chuck Todd in that. Rachel Maddow was a legit star. And none of those people rose to the occasion last night. None of them were competitive enough, none of them filled up the screen enough. If you can put Donald Trump on the stage next to any of these people in a one-on-one, he'd eat their lunch, clean their clock. It wouldn't even be competitive. And I'm not so sure there's anybody tonight that's going to be like that either. Donny is thinking with his heart, Lawrence is thinking with his head. It's not science. They say it's political science, but politics is about emotion, it's about a connection you have - a visceral connection with a candidate and whether you can make that connection with the people, and that's unbreakable. And right now no one's even close to doing that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You be not even Eric Swalwell?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Not even little there.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: His claim to fame is an ad about a poopy diaper. So Donny Deutsch said last night, this is about who is the bully that can beat the bully. The guy who would fill up the screen next to Trump was Bill de Blasio and he certainly was a bully. He shouted down Savannah Guthrie when she was trying to go to break last night. So--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It is pretty amazing that this very unlikable person, unpopular person has this basically Don Quixote quest to become the President of the United States. And I'm sure, a bunch of them are looking around going, "Who are you to be here and to tell us that?" As to the argument is there anybody on that stage, remember incumbent Presidents usually get reelected, especially if there's a good economy. And even if people were like, "Well, he's not really kind of guy", but they're not going to sacrifice their financial security for four years for somebody who can't articulate an economic message. There's not.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think that - well, first of all let me just say. I think that if this was a marketplace for who is the bellowing, bullying candidate, well how are you going to beat Trump, right? But who's going to - you start a debate and the first question is about, "You insult so many women" and then it blows up that's a Trump type of thing. So if it's about personality. But I think that right now, remember politics moves in cycles, Jesse. So people are used to Trump bellowing and bullying and name-calling. So maybe people are interested now in someone who's a problem solver, who has real ideas. Probably someone who says I can get stuff done. I'm just not going to sit around and insult and I'm not going to of the control--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Trump is--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: --of the House and the Senate and not--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
